FrmAndLnRfrncDsc: PART IV, SECTION E, LINE 2A:
ExplntnTxt: THE FACULTY CLUB AT THE UNIVERSITY OF CALIFORNIA SAN DIEGO (UCSD) IS PHYSICALLY LOCATED ON THE UCSD CAMPUS WITH A LONG-TERM LEASE FROM THE UNIVERSITY. THE CLUB WAS FOUNDED IN 1988 TO PROVIDE A PLACE IN A CENTRAL LOCATION FOR COLLEAGUES AND COMMUNITY TO SOCIALIZE AND INTELLECTUALIZE OVER FOOD IN A CASUAL ATMOSPHERE OF UCSD. MEMBERSHIP IN THE CLUB IS REQUIRED FOR PARTICIPATION AND IS LIMITED TO FACULTY, STAFF AND GRADUATE STUDENTS AS WELL AS RETIRED EMPLOYEES, COMMUNITY MEMBERS WITH AN INTEREST IN THE EDUCATIONAL AND INTELLECTUAL LIFE OF THE CAMPUS, PERSONS AT OTHER SELECT NON-PROFIT RESEARCH INSTITUTIONS, CHANCELLORS ASSOCIATES AND SELECT BUSINESSES ADDING TO THE EDUCATIONAL AND INTELLECTUAL LIFE OF THE CAMPUS (MUST BE APPROVED BY 2/3 VOTE OF THE BOARD), AND CAMPUS DEPARTMENTS. LUNCHEON MEALS ARE SERVED WEEKDAYS AND PERIODIC SPECIAL EVENTS ARE SCHEDULED.

FrmAndLnRfrncDsc: PART IV, SECTION E, LINE 2B:
ExplntnTxt: WITHOUT THE FACULTY CLUB, NO SINGLE SPACE OF SUFFICIENT SIZE WOULD BE AVAILABLE REGULARLY NOR MEALS SERVED. THE CASUAL ATMOSPHERE AND CENTRAL LOCATION OF THE CLUB SERVES AS A FOCAL POINT FOR UNIVERSITY EMPLOYEES AND SUPPORTERS. IT ALLOWS FORMAL AND INFORMAL GATHERINGS OF UNIVERSITY COLLEAGUES AND A MEETING PLACE FOR ACTIVITIES. SOME OF THESE ACTIVITIES WOULD CONTINUE ON AN AD HOC BASIS IN THE ABSENCE OF THE CLUB, BUT THE CLUB WAS ESTABLISHED TO FACILITATE THESE INTERACTIONS.

FrmAndLnRfrncDsc: SCHEDULE A, PART IV, SECTION A, LINE 6
ExplntnTxt: THE MISSION OF THE RESEARCH FOUNDATION IS TO SUPPORT OUR MEMBERS IN IMPROVING THE HEALTH OF ALL SOUTH CAROLINIANS BY COLLABORATING ACROSS THE STATE OF SOUTH CAROLINA, REGIONALLY, AND NATIONALLY. GRANT FUNDS WERE PROVIDED TO NON-SUPPORTED ORGANIZATIONS PARTICIPATING IN THE SOUTH CAROLINA SURGICAL QUALITY COLLABORATIVE (SCSQC) AND CAROLINAS COLLABORATIVE. THE RESEARCH FOUNDATION WAS AWARDED FUNDING FROM AN EXTERNAL SOURCE FOR THE SCSQC TO IMPROVE SURGICAL QUALITY SAFETY IN THE STATE. THE COLLABORATIVE HAS PARTNERED WITH SURGICAL LEADERS AT HOSPITALS (SUPPORTED ORGANIZATIONS AND NON-SUPPORTED ORGANIZATIONS) ACROSS THE STATE TO ESTABLISH A CONTINUOUS QUALITY IMPROVEMENT STRUCTURE AND LEARNING HEALTHCARE SYSTEM. EACH PARTICIPATING HOSPITAL RECEIVED FUNDS DURING THE GRANT PERIOD FOR KEY PERSONNEL ALLOCATED TO THE EFFORTS OF THE COLLABORATIVE. THE PARTICIPATING INSTITUTIONS RECEIVED FUNDS DURING THE GRANT PERIOD FOR KEY PERSONNEL ALLOCATED TO INFRASTRUCTURE DEVELOPMENT AND RESEARCH INITIATIVES.

THE COMPONENT UNIT IS INCLUDED IN THE REPORTING ENTITY BECAUSE OF THE SIGNIFICANCE OF ITS OPERATIONAL AND FINANCIAL RELATIONSHIPS WITH THE LSU SYSTEM AND THE LSUHSC. THIS BLENDING PROVIDES THE LSU SYSTEM AND LSUHSC WITH FULL KNOWLEDGE OF THE FINANCIAL MATTERS OF LSUHN.

IN ADDITION, THESE INDIVIDUALS PREPARE THE INSTUTUTE'S BUDGET WHICH IS REVIEWED, MODIFIED AND THEN APPROVED BY THE FOUNDATION'S BOARD. THE BUDGET IS THE BASIS FOR THE CONTRIBUTIONS GRANTED BY THE FOUNDATION TO MASI.

ExplntnTxt: TECHNOLOGY TRANSFER IS CLOSELY LINKED TO FUNDAMENTAL RESEARCH ACTIVITIES IN UNIVERSITIES. UNDER THE BAYH-DOLE ACT OF 1980, UNIVERSITIES HAVE THE ABILITY TO RETAIN TITLE TO AND PROMOTE THE COMMERCIALIZATION OF INVENTIONS DEVELOPED UNDER GOVERNMENT FUNDING. WITH THIS ELECTION, UNIVERSITIES ARE REQUIRED TO PROPERLY MANAGE THE INVENTIONS INCLUDING REPORTING REQUIREMENTS, FILING PATENTS, MARKETING AND LICENSING THE INVENTION AND DISTRIBUTING RETURNS. THE REQUIREMENTS NECESSARY TO ADHERE TO THE BAYH-DOLE ACT ARE CONTRACTED TO KANSAS STATE UNIVERSITY RESEARCH FOUNDATION BY KSU. IF THE KANSAS STATE UNIVERSITY RESEARCH FOUNDATION DID NOT EXIST, KSU WOULD STILL BE REQUIRED TO CONFORM TO THESE REQUIREMENTS.

ExplntnTxt: UNIVERSITY OF TOLEDO PHYSICIANS CLINICAL FACULTY, INC. (UTP) HAS ONLY ONE CLASS OF MEMBER, AND ONLY ONE MEMBER, THE UNIVERSITY OF TOLEDO. THE SOLE MEMBER OF UTP HAS THE POWER TO NOMINATE, ELECT AND REMOVE THE BOARD OF DIRECTORS OF THE CORPORATION; APPROVE AMENDMENTS TO THE ARTICLES OF INCORPORATION AND CODE OF REGULATIONS OF THE CORPORATION; AND EXERCISE SUCH OTHER POWERS AS ARE NECESSARY, APPROPRIATE, AND CONSISTENT WITH LAW AND WITH THE ARTICLES OF INCORPORATION AND THE CODE OF REGULATIONS OF THE CORPORATION. THE FOLLOWING ACTIONS REQUIRE PRIOR APPROVAL OF THE SOLE MEMBER: (A) ANY CHANGE IN THE PURPOSE OR MISSION OF THE CORPORATION; (B) ANY CHANGE IN THE CODE OF REGULATIONS OR ARTICLES OF INCORPORATION OF THE CORPORATION; (C) ANY MERGER OR CONSOLIDATION OF THE CORPORATION WITH AN UNRELATED ENTITY; (D) THE PROPOSED SALE OF ALL OR SUBSTANTIALLY ALL OF THE CORPORATION'S ASSETS; (E) ANY BORROWING OF FUNDS BY THE CORPORATION (EXCLUDING TRADE PAYABLES OR OTHER ORDINARY COURSE INDEBTEDNESS) IN EXCESS OF ITS GENERAL OPERATING LINE OF CREDIT IN AN AMOUNT TO BE ESTABLISHED ON AN ANNUAL BASIS BY APPROVAL OF THE BOARD OR ANY LOAN OF FUNDS BY THE CORPORATION; (F) ANY MATERIAL CHANGES IN THE CORPORATION'S PROFESSIONAL LIABILITY INSURANCE COVERAGE, INCLUDING CHANGES IN THE PARTIES PROVIDING SUCH COVERAGE; AND (G) THE DISSOLUTION OR LIQUIDATION OF THE CORPORATION.
